  <description type="1">
   <narrative xml:lang="EN">The possibility of implementing a project that includes 82 mining concessions, 9 hydroelectric projects and the construction of rural cities in Sierra Norte de Puebla would imply the forced displacement of populations located in the basin of three main rivers: (Ajajalpan, Apulco and Zempoala), the diminishing and poisoning of water reserves, the destruction of the cloud forests and fertile lands in 22 towns that are the sustenance of rural indigenous Nahua and Totonaca families, as well as irreversible damage to health such as cancer, abortions and malformations in newborns. The research conducted up until now suggests that the number of inhabits that would be affected solely in the communities inhabiting these three basins would be 606,859 people. This is without taking into account the effects on the population in the state of Veracruz, in the Tecolutla river basin, where the poisoned water of the Poblano territory would end up. The project involves offering grants to people affected by open-pit mining projects who are members of community organizations, so that they may participate in a training program (certification) for defenders of the land and human rights, which will take place from June to November 2013 in the Centro de Estudios para el Desarrollo Social located in Zautla, Sierra Norte de Puebla. The training process seeks to strengthen knowledge and organizational and technical skills in order to deepen resistance processes in light of dispossession of lands, as well as defense of human rights. Due to the fact that, in Puebla, hydro-mining projects are still in their initial or planning stages, it is essential to learn about the experiences of those affected in other states in which such projects have already been around for a long time, so that, through the exchange of experiences, a plurality of territorial defense strategies that are being implemented in our country can become known. The grants will make it possible for defenders of the land from the states of Chiapas, Morelos, Colima, Guerrero and Veracruz to participate in the program</narrative>
  </description>
